Here the genus is recorded for the first time in 
Brazil
and distributional records of species show clear patterns over the Amazonian lowlands and the North-Central Moist Andes (
Fig. 26
). However, as observed in other groups (e.g. 

; 

; 

) it is not clear if dispersion of species occurred from the Amazon into the Andean region or vice versa. Further investigations on the evolution of the tribe 
Bahitini
and the subfamily 
Deltocephalinae
are needed to clarify the group’s biogeographical history. These South American ecological systems are enormously diverse (

; 

), suggesting that more sampling is needed to assess the diversity of 

Kinrentius

and related genera in both areas.
